{"id":"1208.2847","submitter":"Josef Cibulka","authors":"Josef Cibulka","title":"Maximum size of reverse-free sets of permutations","comments":"10 pages","journal-ref":"SIAM J. Discrete Math., 27(1), 232-239, 2013","doi":"10.1137/120888168","report-no":null,"categories":"math.CO cs.DM","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Two words have a reverse if they have the same pair of distinct letters on\nthe same pair of positions, but in reversed order. A set of words no two of\nwhich have a reverse is said to be reverse-free. Let F(n,k) be the maximum size\nof a reverse-free set of words from [n]^k where no letter repeats within a\nword. We show the following lower and upper bounds in the case n >= k: F(n,k)\n\\in n^k k^{-k/2 + O(k/log k)}. As a consequence of the lower bound, a set of\nn-permutations each two having a reverse has size at most n^{n/2 + O(n/log n)}.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 14 Aug 2012 12:38:57 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 3 Dec 2012 09:34:25 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Thu, 24 Jan 2013 09:35:29 GMT"}],"update_date":"2013-11-12"}
